# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: board-support-package
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed by a team led by French computer scientist Jean Ichbiah of Honeywell under contract to the United States Department of Defense (DoD) from 1977 to 1983 to supersede over 450 programming languages then used by the DoD.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada was named after Ada Lovelace (1815–1852), who has been credited as the first computer programmer.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed for embedded and real-time systems.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Tucker Taft of Intermetrics between 1992 and 1995, improved support for systems, numerical, financial, and object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Features of Ada include strong typing, modular programming mechanisms (packages), run-time checking, parallel processing (tasks, synchronous message passing, protected objects, and nondeterministic select statements), exception handling, and generics.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 added support for object-oriented programming, including dynamic dispatch.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The syntax of Ada minimizes choices of ways to perform basic operations, and prefers English keywords (such as `or else` and `and then`) to symbols (such as `||` and `&&`).
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada uses the basic arithmetical operators `+`, `-`, `*`, and `/`, but avoids using other symbols.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Code blocks are delimited by words such as 'declare', 'begin', and 'end', where the 'end' (in most cases) is followed by the keyword of the block that it closes (e.g., `if` ...
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In the case of conditional blocks this avoids a *dangling else* that could pair with the wrong nested 'if'-expression in other languages such as C or Java.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada is designed for developing very large software systems.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada packages can be compiled separately.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada package specifications (the package interface) can also be compiled separately without the implementation to check for consistency.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This makes it possible to detect problems early during the design phase, before implementation starts.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] A large number of compile-time checks are supported to help avoid bugs that would not be detectable until run time in some other languages or would require explicit checks to be added to the source code.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] For example, the syntax requires explicitly named closing of blocks to prevent errors due to mismatched end tokens.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The adherence to strong typing allows detecting many common software errors (wrong parameters, range violations, invalid references, mismatched types, etc.) either during compile time, or otherwise during run time.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] As concurrency is part of the language specification, the compiler can in some cases detect potential deadlocks.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Compilers also commonly check for misspelled identifiers, visibility of packages, redundant declarations, etc. and can provide warnings and useful suggestions on how to fix the error.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada also supports run-time checks to protect against access to unallocated memory, buffer overflow errors, range violations, off-by-one errors, array access errors, and other detectable bugs.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] These checks can be disabled in the interest of runtime efficiency, but can often be compiled efficiently.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] It also includes facilities to help program verification.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] For these reasons, Ada is sometimes used in critical systems, where any anomaly might lead to very serious consequences, e.g., accidental death, injury or severe financial loss.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Examples of systems where Ada is used include avionics, air traffic control, railways, banking, military and space technology.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada's dynamic memory management is high-level and type-safe.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada has no generic or untyped pointers, nor does it implicitly declare any pointer type.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Instead, all dynamic memory allocation and deallocation must occur via explicitly declared *access types*.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Each access type has an associated *storage pool* that handles the low-level details of memory management; the programmer can either use the default storage pool or define new ones (this is particularly relevant for non-uniform memory access).
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] It is even possible to declare several different access types that all designate the same type but use different storage pools.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Also, the language provides for *accessibility checks*, both at compile time and at run time, that ensures that an *access value* cannot outlive the type of the object it points to.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Though the semantics of the language allow automatic garbage collection of inaccessible objects, most implementations do not support it by default, as it would cause unpredictable behaviour in real-time systems.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada supports a limited form of region-based memory management, and in Ada, destroying a storage pool also destroys all the objects in the pool.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] A double dash (`--`), resembling an em dash, denotes comment text.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Comments stop at end of line; there is intentionally no way to make a comment span multiple lines, to prevent unclosed comments from accidentally voiding whole sections of source code.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Disabling a whole block of code therefore requires the prefixing of each line (or column) individually with `--`.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] While this clearly denotes disabled code by creating a column of repeated '--' down the page, it also renders the experimental dis/re-enablement of large blocks a more drawn-out process in editors without block commenting support.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The semicolon (`;`) is a statement terminator, and the null or no-operation statement is `null;`.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] A single `;` without a statement to terminate is not allowed.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Unlike most ISO standards, the Ada language definition (known as the *Ada Reference Manual* or *ARM*, or sometimes the *Language Reference Manual* or *LRM*) is free content.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Thus, it is a common reference for Ada programmers, not only programmers implementing Ada compilers.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Apart from the reference manual, there is also an extensive rationale document which explains the language design and the use of various language constructs.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This document is also widely used by programmers.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] When the language was revised, a new rationale document was written.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] One notable free software tool that is used by many Ada programmers to aid them in writing Ada source code is the GNAT Programming Studio, and GNAT which is part of the GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In the 1970s the US Department of Defense (DoD) became concerned by the number of different programming languages being used for its embedded computer system projects, many of which were obsolete or hardware-dependent, and none of which supported safe modular programming.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In 1975, a working group, the High Order Language Working Group (HOLWG), was formed with the intent to reduce this number by finding or creating a programming language generally suitable for the department's and the UK Ministry of Defence's requirements.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] After many iterations beginning with an original straw-man proposal the eventual programming language was named Ada.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The total number of high-level programming languages in use for such projects fell from over 450 in 1983 to 37 by 1996.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] HOLWG crafted the **Steelman language requirements**, a series of documents stating the requirements they felt a programming language should satisfy.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Many existing languages were formally reviewed, but the team concluded in 1977 that no existing language met the specifications.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The requirements were created by the United States Department of Defense in *The Department of Defense Common High Order Language program* in 1978.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The predecessors of this document were called, in order, "Strawman", "Woodenman", "Tinman" and "Ironman".
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The requirements focused on the needs of embedded computer applications, and emphasised reliability, maintainability, and efficiency.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Notably, they included exception handling facilities, run-time checking, and parallel computing.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] It was concluded that no existing language met these criteria to a sufficient extent, so a contest was called to create a language that would be closer to fulfilling them.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The design that won this contest became the Ada programming language.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The resulting language followed the Steelman requirements closely, though not exactly.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In April 1978, after public scrutiny, the Red and Green proposals passed to the next phase.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In May 1979, the Green proposal, designed by Jean Ichbiah at Honeywell, was chosen and given the name Ada—after Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace, usually known as Ada Lovelace.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This proposal was influenced by the language LIS that Ichbiah and his group had developed in the 1970s.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The preliminary Ada reference manual was published in ACM SIGPLAN Notices in June 1979.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Military Standard reference manual was approved on December 10, 1980 (Ada Lovelace's birthday), and given the number MIL-STD-1815 in honor of Ada Lovelace's birth year.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In 1981, Tony Hoare took advantage of his Turing Award speech to criticize Ada for being overly complex and hence unreliable, but subsequently seemed to recant in the foreword he wrote for an Ada textbook.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada attracted much attention from the programming community as a whole during its early days.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Its backers and others predicted that it might become a dominant language for general purpose programming and not only defense-related work.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ichbiah publicly stated that within ten years, only two programming languages would remain: Ada and Lisp.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Early Ada compilers struggled to implement the large, complex language, and both compile-time and run-time performance tended to be slow and tools primitive.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Compiler vendors expended most of their efforts in passing the massive, language-conformance-testing, government-required Ada Compiler Validation Capability (ACVC) validation suite that was required in another novel feature of the Ada language effort.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The first validated Ada implementation was the NYU Ada/Ed translator, certified on April 11, 1983.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] NYU Ada/Ed is implemented in the high-level set language SETL.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Several commercial companies began offering Ada compilers and associated development tools, including Alsys, TeleSoft, DDC-I, Advanced Computer Techniques, Tartan Laboratories, Irvine Compiler, TLD Systems, and Verdix.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] In 1991, the US Department of Defense began to require the use of Ada (the *Ada mandate*) for all software, though exceptions to this rule were often granted.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Department of Defense Ada mandate was effectively removed in 1997, as the DoD began to embrace commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) technology.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Similar requirements existed in other NATO countries: Ada was required for NATO systems involving command and control and other functions, and Ada was the mandated or preferred language for defense-related applications in countries such as Sweden, Germany, and Canada.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] By the late 1980s and early 1990s, Ada compilers had improved in performance, but there were still barriers to fully exploiting Ada's abilities, including a tasking model that was different from what most real-time programmers were used to.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Canadian Automated Air Traffic System was written in 1 million lines of Ada (SLOC count).
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] It featured advanced distributed processing, a distributed Ada database, and object-oriented design.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada is also used in other air traffic systems, e.g., the UK's next-generation Interim Future Area Control Tools Support (iFACTS) air traffic control system is designed and implemented using SPARK Ada.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] It is also used in the French TVM in-cab signalling system on the TGV high-speed rail system, and the metro suburban trains in Paris, London, Hong Kong and New York City.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Ada 95 revision of the language went beyond the Steelman requirements, targeting general-purpose systems in addition to embedded ones, and adding features supporting object-oriented programming.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada was first published in 1980 as an ANSI standard ANSI/**MIL-STD 1815**.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] As this very first version held many errors and inconsistencies, the revised edition was published in 1983 as ANSI/MIL-STD 1815A.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Without any further changes, it became an ISO standard in 1987.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This version of the language is commonly known as **Ada 83**, from the date of its adoption by ANSI, but is sometimes referred to also as **Ada 87**, from the date of its adoption by ISO.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] There is also a French translation; DIN translated it into German as DIN 66268 in 1988.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Work has continued on improving and updating the technical content of the Ada language.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] A Technical Corrigendum to Ada 95 was published in October 2001, and a major Amendment, ISO/IEC 8652:1995/Amd 1:2007 was published on March 9, 2007, commonly known as **Ada 2005** because work on the new standard was finished that year.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Ada-based SPARK technology has been made possible by the enabling characteristics of the Ada language, including its separation of specification and implementation via packages, its support for user-defined scalar types, and its support for composite type usage without resorting to pointers.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The Ada 2012 revision was especially important for SPARK, as its support for contracts as a part of the language permitted SPARK to be redesigned from the beginning towards fulfilling its goal of co-developing programs alongside their proofs of correctness.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] On May 2, 2023, the Ada community saw the formal approval of publication of the **Ada 2022** edition of the programming language standard.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Despite the names Ada 83, 95 etc., legally there is only one Ada standard, the last ISO/IEC standard: with the acceptance of a new standard version, the previous one becomes withdrawn.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The other names are informal ones referencing a certain edition.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Other related standards include ISO/IEC 8651-3:1988 *Information processing systems—Computer graphics—Graphical Kernel System (GKS) language bindings—Part 3: Ada*.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada is an ALGOL-like programming language featuring control structures with reserved words such as *if*, *then*, *else*, *while*, *for*, and so on.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] However, Ada also has many data structuring facilities and other abstractions which were not included in the original ALGOL 60, such as type definitions, records, pointers, and enumerations.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited from or inspired by Pascal.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada's type system is not based on a set of predefined primitive types but allows users to declare their own types.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This declaration in turn is not based on the internal representation of the type but on describing the goal which should be achieved.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] This allows the compiler to determine a suitable memory size for the type, and to check for violations of the type definition at compile time and run time (i.e., range violations, buffer overruns, type consistency, etc.).
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada supports numerical types defined by a range, modulo types, aggregate types (records and arrays), and enumeration types.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Access types define a reference to an instance of a specified type; untyped pointers are not permitted.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Special types provided by the language are task types and protected types.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] The predefined plus operator can only add values of the same type, so the expression is illegal.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Types can have modifiers such as *limited, abstract, private* etc.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Private types do not show their inner structure; objects of limited types cannot be copied.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 adds further features for object-oriented extension of types.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Ada is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] All standard constructs and deep-level early exit are supported, so the use of the also supported "go to" commands is seldom needed.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Among the parts of an Ada program are packages, procedures and functions.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Functions differ from procedures in that they must return a value.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Function calls cannot be used "as a statement", and their result must be assigned to a variable.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] However, since Ada 2012, functions are not required to be pure and may mutate their suitably declared parameters or the global state.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Packages, procedures and functions can nest to any depth, and each can also be the logical outermost block.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Each package, procedure or function can have its own declarations of constants, types, variables, and other procedures, functions and packages, which can be declared in any order.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] A pragma is a compiler directive that conveys information to the compiler to allow specific manipulating of compiled output.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Certain pragmas are built into the language, while others are implementation-specific.
[src:board-support-package/ada-programming-language] Examples of common usage of compiler pragmas would be to disable certain features, such as run-time type checking or array subscript boundary checking, or to instruct the compiler to insert object code instead of a function call (as C/C++ does with inline functions).
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] ash was first released via a posting to the comp.sources.unix Usenet news group, approved and moderated by Rich Salz on 30 May 1989.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] It was described as "a reimplementation of the System V shell [with] most features of that shell, plus some additions".
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Fast, small, and virtually compatible with the POSIX standard's specification of the Unix shell, ash did not provide line editing or command history mechanisms, because Almquist felt that such functionality should be moved into the terminal driver.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Myriad forks have been produced from the original ash release.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] These derivatives of ash are installed as the default shell (`/bin/sh`) on FreeBSD, NetBSD, DragonFly BSD, MINIX, and in some Linux distributions.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] MINIX 3.2 used the original ash version, whose test feature differed from POSIX.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] That version of the shell was replaced in MINIX 3.3.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Android used ash until Android 4.0, at which point it switched to mksh.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Chimera Linux uses FreeBSD's version of the ash as its default, which is quite unique in the Linux realm.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] In 1997 Herbert Xu ported `ash` from NetBSD to Debian Linux.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] In September 2002, with release 0.4.1, this port was renamed to **Dash** (**Debian Almquist shell**).
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Xu's main priorities are POSIX conformance and slim implementation.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Like its predecessor, Dash implements support for neither internationalization and localization nor multi-byte character encoding (both required in POSIX).
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Line editing and history support based on GNU Readline is optional (`--with-libedit`).
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Because of its slimness, Ubuntu decided to adopt Dash as the default `/bin/sh` in October 2006 with version 6.10.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] The reason for using Dash is faster shell script execution, especially during startup of the operating system, compared to previous versions of Debian and Ubuntu that used Bash for this purpose, although Bash is still the default login shell for interactive use.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] A result of the shift is that many shell scripts were found making use of Bash-specific functionalities ("bashisms") without properly declaring it in the shebang line.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] The problem was first spotted in Ubuntu and the maintainers decided to make all the scripts comply with the POSIX standard.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] The changes were later upstreamed to Debian, which eventually adopted Dash as its default `/bin/sh` too in Debian 6 (Squeeze), released in February 2011.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] As a result, Debian policy was amended to allow script developers to assume a largely POSIX-compliant shell, save for the extensions merged into Dash for convenience (`local`, `echo -n`, `test -a / -o`).
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] A similar transition has happened in Slackware Linux, although its version of `ash` is only partially based on Dash.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Ash (mainly the Dash fork) is also fairly popular in embedded Linux systems.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Dash version 0.3.8-5 was incorporated into BusyBox, the catch-all executable often employed in this area.
[src:board-support-package/almquist-shell] Modern BusyBox versions support additional Bash features which are enabled in modern distributions like Alpine Linux, Tiny Core Linux and Linux-based router firmware such as OpenWrt, Tomato and DD-WRT.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] At its core, the operating system is known as the **Android Open Source Project** (**AOSP**) and is free and open-source software (FOSS) primarily licensed under the Apache License.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Other Google services including Firebase Cloud Messaging, used for push notifications, are recommended for applications.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] While AOSP is free, the "Android" name and logo are trademarks of Google, who restrict the use of Android branding on "uncertified" products.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The majority of smartphones based on AOSP run Google's ecosystem—which is known simply as Android—some with vendor-customized user interfaces and software suites, for example One UI.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Commercial products like micro consoles and virtual reality headset have also used Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2011 Android has been the most used operating system worldwide on smartphones.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] It has the largest installed base of any operating system in the world with over three billion monthly active users and accounting for 46% of the global operating system market.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In 2005, Rubin tried to negotiate deals with Samsung and HTC.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Shortly afterwards, Google acquired the company in July of that year for at least $50 million; this was Google's "best deal ever" according to Google's then-vice president of corporate development, David Lawee, in 2010.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android's key employees, including Rubin, Miner, Sears, and White, joined Google as part of the acquisition.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Not much was known about the secretive Android Inc. at the time, with the company having provided few details other than that it was making software for mobile phones.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] At Google, the team led by Rubin developed a mobile device platform powered by the Linux kernel.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google marketed the platform to handset makers and carriers on the promise of providing a flexible, upgradeable system.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google had "lined up a series of hardware components and software partners and signaled to carriers that it was open to various degrees of cooperation".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Speculation about Google's intention to enter the mobile communications market continued to build through December 2006.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] An early prototype had a close resemblance to a BlackBerry phone, with no touchscreen and a physical QWERTY keyboard, but the arrival of Apple's 2007 iPhone meant that Android "had to go back to the drawing board".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google later changed its Android specification documents to state that "Touchscreens will be supported", although "the Product was designed with the presence of discrete physical buttons as an assumption, therefore a touchscreen cannot completely replace physical buttons".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] By 2008, both Nokia and BlackBerry announced touch-based smartphones to rival the iPhone 3G, and Android's focus eventually switched to just touchscreens.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The first commercially available smartphone running Android was the HTC Dream, also known as T-Mobile G1, announced on September 23, 2008.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Within a year, the Open Handset Alliance faced two other open source competitors, the Symbian Foundation and the LiMo Foundation, the latter also developing a Linux-based mobile operating system like Google.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In September 2007, Google had filed several patent applications in the area of mobile telephony.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On September 23, 2008, Android was introduced by Andy Rubin, Larry Page, Sergey Brin, Cole Brodman, Christopher Schlaeffer and Peter Chou at a press conference in a New York City subway station.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2008, Android has seen numerous updates which have incrementally improved the operating system, adding new features and fixing bugs in previous releases.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In 2010, Google launched its Nexus series of devices, a lineup in which Google partnered with different device manufacturers to produce new devices and introduce new Android versions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The series was described as having "played a pivotal role in Android's history by introducing new software iterations and hardware standards across the board", and became known for its "bloat-free" software with "timely ... updates".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] At its developer conference in May 2013, Google announced a special version of the Samsung Galaxy S4, where, instead of using Samsung's own Android customization, the phone ran "stock Android" and was promised to receive new system updates fast.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The device would become the start of the Google Play edition program, and was followed by other devices, including the HTC One Google Play edition, and Moto G Google Play edition.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In 2015, *Ars Technica* wrote that "Earlier this week, the last of the Google Play edition Android phones in Google's online storefront were listed as "no longer available for sale" and that "Now they're all gone, and it looks a whole lot like the program has wrapped up".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] From 2008 to 2013, Hugo Barra served as product spokesperson, representing Android at press conferences and Google I/O, Google's annual developer-focused conference.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] He left Google in August 2013 to join Chinese phone maker Xiaomi.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Less than six months earlier, Google's then-CEO Larry Page announced in a blog post that Andy Rubin had moved from the Android division to take on new projects at Google, and that Sundar Pichai would become the new Android lead.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Pichai himself would eventually switch positions, becoming the new CEO of Google in August 2015 following the company's restructure into the Alphabet conglomerate, making Hiroshi Lockheimer the new head of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On Android 4.4, *KitKat*, shared writing access to MicroSD memory cards has been locked for user-installed applications, to which only the dedicated directories with respective package names, located inside `Android/data/`, remained writeable.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Writing access has been reinstated with Android 5 *Lollipop* through the backwards-incompatible *Google Storage Access Framework* interface.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In June 2014, Google announced Android One, a set of "hardware reference models" that would "allow [device makers] to easily create high-quality phones at low costs", designed for consumers in developing countries.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In September, Google announced the first set of Android One phones for release in India.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] However, *Recode* reported in June 2015 that the project was "a disappointment", citing "reluctant consumers and manufacturing partners" and "misfires from the search company that has never quite cracked hardware".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Plans to relaunch Android One surfaced in August 2015, with Africa announced as the next location for the program a week later.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] A report from *The Information* in January 2017 stated that Google is expanding its low-cost Android One program into the United States, although *The Verge* notes that the company will presumably not produce the actual devices itself.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google introduced the Pixel and Pixel XL smartphones in October 2016, marketed as being the first phones made by Google, and exclusively featured certain software features, such as the Google Assistant, before wider rollout.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The Pixel phones replaced the Nexus series, with a new generation of Pixel phones launched in October 2017.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In May 2019, the operating system became entangled in the trade war between China and the United States involving Huawei, which, like many other tech firms, had become dependent on access to the Android platform.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In the summer of 2019, Huawei announced it would create an alternative operating system to Android known as Harmony OS, and has filed for intellectual property rights across major global markets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Under such sanctions Huawei has long-term plans to replace Android in 2022 with the new operating system, as Harmony OS was originally designed for internet of things devices, rather than for smartphones and tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On August 22, 2019, it was announced that Android "Q" would officially be branded as Android 10, ending the historic practice of naming major versions after desserts.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google stated that these names were not "inclusive" to international users (due either to the aforementioned foods not being internationally known, or being difficult to pronounce in some languages).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On the same day, *Android Police* reported that Google had commissioned a statue of a giant number "10" to be installed in the lobby of the developers' new office.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android 10 was released on September 3, 2019, to Google Pixel phones first.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In late 2021, some users reported that they were unable to dial emergency services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The problem was caused by a combination of bugs in Android and in the Microsoft Teams app; both companies released updates addressing the issue.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On December 12, 2024, Google announced Android XR.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] It is a new operating system developed by Google, designed for virtual reality and augmented reality devices, such as VR headsets and smart glasses.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] It was built in collaboration with Samsung and Qualcomm.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The platform is also focused on supporting developers with tools like ARCore and Unity to build applications for upcoming XR devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In March 2025, Google announced its plans to consolidate Android development to internal sources.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] While public developers will no longer be able to contribute, the Android source will still be published.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android's default user interface is mainly based on direct manipulation, using touch inputs that loosely correspond to real-world actions, like swiping, tapping, pinching, and reverse pinching to manipulate on-screen objects, along with a virtual keyboard.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Game controllers and full-size physical keyboards are supported via Bluetooth or USB.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The response to user input is designed to be immediate and provides a fluid touch interface, often using the vibration capabilities of the device to provide haptic feedback to the user.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices boot to the home screen, the primary navigation and information "hub" on Android devices, analogous to the desktop found on personal computers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android home screens are typically made up of app icons and widgets; app icons launch the associated app, whereas widgets display live, auto-updating content, such as a weather forecast, the user's email inbox, or a news ticker directly on the home screen.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] A home screen may be made up of several pages, between which the user can swipe back and forth.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Third-party apps available on Google Play and other app stores can extensively re-theme the home screen, and even mimic the look of other operating systems, such as Windows Phone.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Most manufacturers customize the look and features of their Android devices to differentiate themselves from their competitors.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] This status bar can be pulled (swiped) down to reveal a notification screen where apps display important information or updates, as well as quick access to system controls and toggles such as display brightness, connectivity settings (WiFi, Bluetooth, cellular data), audio mode, and flashlight.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Vendors may implement extended settings such as the ability to adjust the flashlight brightness.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Notifications are "short, timely, and relevant information about your app when it's not in use", and when tapped, users are directed to a screen inside the app relating to the notification.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Beginning with Android 4.1 "Jelly Bean", "expandable notifications" allow the user to tap an icon on the notification in order for it to expand and display more information and possible app actions right from the notification.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] An "All Apps" screen lists all installed applications, with the ability for users to drag an app from the list onto the home screen.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The app list may be accessed using a gesture or a button, depending on the Android version.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] A "Recents" screen, also known as "Overview", lets users switch between recently used apps.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The recent list may appear side-by-side or overlapping, depending on the Android version and manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Many early Android OS smartphones were equipped with a dedicated search button for quick access to a web search engine and individual apps' internal search feature.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] More recent devices typically allow the former through a long press or swipe away from the home button.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The dedicated option key, also known as menu key, and its on-screen simulation, is no longer supported since Android version 10.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google recommends mobile application developers to locate menus within the user interface.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] On more recent phones, its place is occupied by a task key used to access the list of recently used apps when actuated.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Depending on device, its long press may simulate a menu button press or engage split screen view, the latter of which is the default behaviour since stock Android version 7.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Native support for split screen view has been added in stock Android version 7.0 *Nougat*.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The earliest vendor-customized Android-based smartphones known to have featured a split-screen view mode are the 2012 Samsung Galaxy S3 and Note 2, the former of which received this feature with the *premium suite* upgrade delivered in TouchWiz with Android 4.1 Jelly Bean.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android has supported a rudimentary Desktop Mode in developer options.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] A native desktop mode was rolled out in March 2026 to Pixel devices from the Pixel 8 onward; tablets received it with Android 16 QPR3, with the intention to roll this feature out to more devices in the future.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Most Android devices come with preinstalled Google apps including Gmail, Google Maps, Google Chrome, YouTube, Google TV, and others.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Java is still supported (originally the only option for user-space programs, and is often mixed with Kotlin), as is C++.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Java or other JVM languages, such as Kotlin, may be combined with C/C++, together with a choice of non-default runtimes that allow better C++ support.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The SDK includes a comprehensive set of development tools, including a debugger, software libraries, a handset emulator based on QEMU, documentation, sample code, and tutorials.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Initially, Google's supported integrated development environment (IDE) was Eclipse using the Android Development Tools (ADT) plugin; in December 2014, Google released Android Studio, based on IntelliJ IDEA, as its primary IDE for Android application development.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Other development tools are available, including a native development kit (NDK) for applications or extensions in C or C++, Google App Inventor, a visual environment for novice programmers, and various cross platform mobile web applications frameworks.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In January 2014, Google unveiled a framework based on Apache Cordova for porting Chrome HTML 5 web applications to Android, wrapped in a native application shell.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Additionally, Firebase was acquired by Google in 2014 that provides helpful tools for app and web developers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store is the primary application store installed on Android devices that comply with Google's compatibility requirements and license the Google Mobile Services software.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store allows users to browse, download and update applications published by Google and third-party developers; as of January 2021, there are more than three million applications available for Android in Play Store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] As of July 2013, 50 billion application installations had been performed.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Some carriers offer direct carrier billing for Google Play application purchases, where the cost of the application is added to the user's monthly bill.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] As of May 2017, there are over one billion active users a month for Gmail, Android, Chrome, Google Play and Maps.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Examples of these third-party stores have included the Amazon Appstore, GetJar, and SlideMe.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] F-Droid, another alternative marketplace, seeks to only provide applications that are distributed under free and open source licenses.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In October 2020, Google removed several Android applications from Play Store, as they were identified breaching its data collection rules.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The firm was informed by International Digital Accountability Council (IDAC) that apps for children like *Number Coloring*, *Princess Salon* and *Cats & Cosplay*, with collective downloads of 20 million, were violating Google's policies.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] At the Windows 11 announcement event in June 2021, Microsoft showcased the new Windows Subsystem for Android (WSA) to enable support for the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), but it has since been deprecated.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] It was intended to allow users to run Android apps and games on their Windows 11 desktop.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Microsoft ended WSA support on March 5, 2025.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The storage of Android devices can be expanded using secondary devices such as SD cards.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android recognizes two types of secondary storage: *portable* storage (which is used by default), and *adoptable* storage.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Portable storage is treated as an external storage device.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Adoptable storage, introduced on Android 6.0, allows the internal storage of the device to be spanned with the SD card, treating it as an extension of the internal storage.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] This has the disadvantage of preventing the memory card from being used with another device unless it is reformatted.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android 4.4 introduced the Storage Access Framework (SAF), a set of APIs for accessing files on the device's filesystem.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] As of Android 11, Android has required apps to conform to a data privacy policy known as *scoped storage*, under which apps may only automatically have access to certain directories (such as those for pictures, music, and video), and app-specific directories they have created themselves.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Apps are required to use the SAF to access any other part of the filesystem.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Since Android devices are usually battery-powered, Android is designed to manage processes to keep power consumption at a minimum.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] When an application is not in use the system suspends its operation so that, while available for immediate use rather than closed, it does not use battery power or CPU resources.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android manages the applications stored in memory automatically: when memory is low, the system will begin invisibly and automatically closing inactive processes, starting with those that have been inactive for the longest amount of time.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Lifehacker reported in 2011 that third-party task-killer applications were doing more harm than good.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] "App's Not Responding"), prevent a Bluetooth audio client from controlling the system volume ("Disable absolute volume"), and adjust the duration of transition animations or deactivate them completely to speed up navigation.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Developer options are initially hidden since Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean", but can be enabled by actuating the operating system's build number in the device information seven times.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Hiding developers options again requires deleting user data for the "Settings" app, possibly resetting some other preferences, or in recent Android versions, turning off the Developer options master switch.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The main hardware platform for Android is 64-bit ARM (i.e. the ARMv8-A architecture) and the 32-bit ARMv7-A architecture, with x86-64 and the 32-bit x86 architectures also being officially supported in later versions of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The unofficial Android-x86 project provided support for x86 architectures ahead of the official support.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2012, Android devices with Intel processors began to appear, including phones and tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] While gaining support for 64-bit platforms, Android was first made to run on 64-bit x86 and then on ARM64.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] An unofficial experimental port of the operating system to 64-bit RISC-V architecture was released in 2021.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Requirements for the minimum amount of RAM for smartphones running Android 15 range from 4 GB of RAM for full Android to 2 GB, in which case the smartphone manufacturers must use the Android Go Edition.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android supports all versions of OpenGL ES and Vulkan (and version 1.1 available for some devices).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices incorporate many optional hardware components, including still or video cameras, GPS, orientation sensors, dedicated gaming controls, accelerometers, gyroscopes, barometers, magnetometers, proximity sensors, pressure sensors, thermometers, and touchscreens.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Some hardware components are not required, but became standard in certain classes of devices, such as smartphones, and additional requirements apply if they are present.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Some other hardware was initially required, but those requirements have been relaxed or eliminated altogether.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] For example, as Android was developed initially as a phone OS, hardware such as microphones were required, while over time the phone function became optional.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android used to require an autofocus camera, which was relaxed to a fixed-focus camera if present at all, since the camera was dropped as a requirement entirely when Android started to be used on set-top boxes.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to running on smartphones and tablets, several vendors run Android natively on regular PC hardware with a keyboard and mouse.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to their availability on commercially available hardware, similar PC hardware-friendly versions of Android are freely available from the Android-x86 project, including customized Android 4.4.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Using the Android emulator that is part of the Android SDK, or third-party emulators, Android can also run non-natively on x86 architectures.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Chinese companies are building a PC and mobile operating system, based on Android, to "compete directly with Microsoft Windows and Google Android".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] The Chinese Academy of Engineering noted that "more than a dozen" companies were customizing Android following a Chinese ban on the use of Windows 8 on government PCs.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Android runs on a wide variety of devices such as smartphones, tablets, cars, computers, smart watches, and smart TVs.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] However, the vast majority of Android-powered devices are smartphones.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] Unlike its two main competitors in the mobile operating system space, namely iOS and HarmonyOS, Android devices are made by many different original equipment manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p01] These OEMs include Samsung, Xiaomi, Vivo, Oppo, iQOO, OnePlus, Honor, Google, Sony, Lenovo, Sharp, Realme, Nothing, and Tecno.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android is developed by Google until the latest changes and updates are ready to be released, at which point the source code is made available to the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), an open source initiative led by Google.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The first source code release happened as part of the initial release in 2007.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] All releases are under the Apache License.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The AOSP code can be found with minimal modifications on select devices, mainly the former Nexus and current Android One series of devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, most original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) customize the source code to run on their hardware.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android's source code does not contain the device drivers, often proprietary, that are needed for certain hardware components, and does not contain the source code of Google Play Services, which many apps depend on.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, most Android devices, including Google's own, ship with a combination of free and open source and proprietary software, with the software required for accessing Google services falling into the latter category.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this, there are some projects that build complete operating systems based on AOSP as free software, the first being CyanogenMod (see section Open-source community below).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google provides annual Android releases, both for factory installation in new devices, and for over-the-air updates to existing devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The extensive variation of hardware in Android devices has caused significant delays for software upgrades and security patches.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Each upgrade has had to be specifically tailored, a time- and resource-consuming process.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Except for devices within the Google Nexus and Pixel brands, updates have often arrived months after the release of the new version, or not at all.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers often prioritize their newest devices and leave old ones behind.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Additional delays can be introduced by wireless carriers who, after receiving updates from manufacturers, further customize Android to their needs and conduct extensive testing on their networks before sending out the upgrade.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] There are also situations in which upgrades are impossible due to a manufacturer not updating necessary drivers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The lack of after-sale support from manufacturers and carriers has been widely criticized by consumer groups and the technology media.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Some commentators have noted that the industry has a financial incentive not to upgrade their devices, as the lack of updates for existing devices fuels the purchase of newer ones, an attitude described as "insulting".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] *The Guardian* complained that the method of distribution for updates is complicated only because manufacturers and carriers have designed it that way.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2011, Google partnered with a number of industry players to announce an "Android Update Alliance", pledging to deliver timely updates for every device for 18 months after its release; however, there has not been another official word about that alliance since its announcement.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2012, Google began de-coupling certain aspects of the operating system (particularly its central applications) so they could be updated through the Google Play store independently of the OS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] One of those components, Google Play Services, is a closed-source system-level process providing APIs for Google services, installed automatically on nearly all devices running Android 2.2 "Froyo" and higher.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] With these changes, Google can add new system functions and update apps without having to distribute an upgrade to the operating system itself.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android 4.2 and 4.3 "Jelly Bean" contained relatively fewer user-facing changes, focusing more on minor changes and platform improvements.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] HTC's then-executive Jason Mackenzie called monthly security updates "unrealistic" in 2015, and Google was trying to persuade carriers to exclude security patches from the full testing procedures.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As stated by *Bloomberg*: "As smartphones get more capable, complex and hackable, having the latest software work closely with the hardware is increasingly important".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Hiroshi Lockheimer, the Android lead, admitted that "It's not an ideal situation", further commenting that the lack of updates is "the weakest link on security on Android".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Wireless carriers were described in the report as the "most challenging discussions", due to their slow approval time while testing on their networks, despite some carriers, including Verizon Wireless and Sprint Corporation, already shortening their approval times.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In a further effort for persuasion, Google shared a list of top phone makers measured by updated devices with its Android partners, and is considering making the list public.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Mike Chan, co-founder of phone maker Nextbit and former Android developer, said that "The best way to solve this problem is a massive re-architecture of the operating system", "or Google could invest in training manufacturers and carriers 'to be good Android citizens'".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2017, with the announcement of Android 8.0, Google introduced Project Treble, a major re-architect of the Android OS framework designed to make it easier, faster, and less costly for manufacturers to update devices to newer versions of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Project Treble separates the vendor implementation (device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new "vendor interface".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 7.0 and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists, so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of the operating system.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2019, with the announcement of Android 10, Google introduced Project Mainline to simplify and expedite delivery of updates to the Android ecosystem.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Project Mainline enables updates to core OS components through the Google Play Store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, important security and performance improvements that previously needed to be part of full OS updates can be downloaded and installed as easily as an app update.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google reported rolling out new amendments in Android 12 aimed at making the use of third-party application stores easier.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This announcement rectified the concerns reported regarding the development of Android apps, including a fight over an alternative in-app payment system and difficulties faced by businesses moving online because of COVID-19.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android's kernel is based on the Linux kernel's long-term support (LTS) branches.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The actual kernel depends on the individual device.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android's variant of the Linux kernel has further architectural changes that are implemented by Google outside the typical Linux kernel development cycle, such as the inclusion of components like device trees, ashmem, ION, and different out of memory (OOM) handling.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Certain features that Google contributed back to the Linux kernel, notably a power management feature called "wakelocks", were initially rejected by mainline kernel developers partly because they felt that Google did not show any intent to maintain its own code.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google engineer Patrick Brady once stated in the company's developer conference that "Android is not Linux", with *Computerworld* adding that "Let me make it simple for you, without Linux, there is no Android".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] *Ars Technica* wrote that "Although Android is built on top of the Linux kernel, the platform has very little in common with the conventional desktop Linux stack".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2011, Linus Torvalds said that "eventually Android and Linux would come back to a common kernel, but it will probably not be for four to five years".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2011, Greg Kroah-Hartman announced the start of Android Mainlining Project, which aims to put some Android drivers, patches and features back into the Linux kernel, starting in Linux 3.3.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Linux included the autosleep and wakelocks capabilities in the 3.5 kernel, after many previous attempts at a merger.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The interfaces are the same but the upstream Linux implementation allows for two different suspend modes: to memory (the traditional suspend that Android uses), and to disk (hibernate, as it is known on the desktop).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains a public code repository that contains their experimental work to re-base Android off the latest stable Linux versions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android is a Linux distribution according to the Linux Foundation, Google's open-source chief Chris DiBona, and several journalists.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, say that Android is not Linux in the traditional Unix-like Linux distribution sense; Android does not include the GNU C Library (it uses Bionic as an alternative C library) and some other components typically found in Linux distributions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] With the release of Android Oreo in 2017, Google began to require that devices shipped with new SoCs had Linux kernel version 4.4 or newer, for security reasons.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Existing devices upgraded to Oreo, and new products launched with older SoCs, were exempt from this rule.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The flash storage on Android devices is split into several partitions, such as `/system/` for the operating system itself, and `/data/` for user data and application installations.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In contrast to typical desktop Linux distributions, Android device owners are not given root access to the operating system and sensitive partitions such as `/system/` are partially read-only.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, root access can be obtained by exploiting security flaws in Android, which is used frequently by the open-source community to enhance the capabilities and customizability of their devices, but also by malicious parties to install viruses and malware.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The unlocking process resets the system to factory state, erasing all user data.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Proprietary frameworks like Samsung Knox limit or block attempts at rooting.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google's Play Integrity API allows developers to check for any signs of tampering, although the fairness of the tests have been criticized.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] On top of the Linux kernel, there are the middleware, libraries and APIs written in C, and application software running on an application framework which includes Java-compatible libraries.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Development of the Linux kernel continues independently of Android's other source code projects.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android uses Android Runtime (ART) as its runtime environment (introduced in version 4.4), which uses ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation to entirely compile the application bytecode into machine code upon the installation of an application.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 4.4, ART was an experimental feature and not enabled by default; it became the only runtime option in the next major version of Android, 5.0.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In versions no longer supported, until version 5.0 when ART took over, Android previously used Dalvik as a process virtual machine with trace-based just-in-time (JIT) compilation to run Dalvik "dex-code" (Dalvik Executable), which is usually translated from the Java bytecode.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Following the trace-based JIT principle, in addition to interpreting the majority of application code, Dalvik performs the compilation and native execution of select frequently executed code segments ("traces") each time an application is launched.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] For its Java library, the Android platform uses a subset of the now discontinued Apache Harmony project.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2015, Google announced that the next version of Android would switch to a Java implementation based on the OpenJDK project.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android's standard C library, Bionic, was developed by Google specifically for Android, as a derivation of the BSD's standard C library code.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Bionic itself has been designed with several major features specific to the Linux kernel.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The main benefits of using Bionic instead of the GNU C Library (glibc) or uClibc are its smaller runtime footprint, and optimization for low-frequency CPUs.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] At the same time, Bionic is licensed under the terms of the BSD licence, which Google finds more suitable for the Android's overall licensing model.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Aiming for a different licensing model, toward the end of 2012, Google switched the Bluetooth stack in Android from the GPL-licensed BlueZ to the Apache-licensed BlueDroid.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] A new Bluetooth stack, called Gabeldorsche, was developed to try to fix the bugs in the BlueDroid implementation.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android does not have a native X Window System by default, nor does it support the full set of standard GNU libraries.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This made it difficult to port existing Linux applications or libraries to Android, until version r5 of the Android Native Development Kit brought support for applications written completely in C or C++.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Libraries written in C may also be used in applications by injection of a small shim and usage of the JNI.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In current versions of Android, "Toybox", a collection of command-line utilities (mostly for use by apps, as Android does not provide a command-line interface by default), is used (since the release of Marshmallow) replacing a similar "Toolbox" collection found in previous Android versions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Community releases often come pre-rooted and contain modifications not provided by the original vendor, such as the ability to overclock or over/undervolt the device's processor, or security enhancements beyond what is included in the stock OS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] CyanogenMod was the most widely used community firmware; after its abrupt discontinuation in 2016, a community fork known as LineageOS was established as a spiritual continuation of the project.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Historically, device manufacturers and mobile carriers have typically been unsupportive of third-party firmware development.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers express concern about improper functioning of devices running unofficial software and the support costs resulting from this.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Moreover, modified firmware such as CyanogenMod sometimes offer features, such as tethering, for which carriers would otherwise charge a premium.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, technical obstacles including locked bootloaders and restricted access to root permissions are common in many devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, despite manufacturer acceptance, some carriers in the US still require that phones are locked down.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android was also ported by the community to Apple's iPhone, iPad and iPod touch devices as a consequence of porting the Linux kernel on Apple devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2010, OpeniBoot and subsequently iDroid were released to allow dual booting iOS and Android 2.3.3 'Gingerbread' on jailbroken iPhone or iPod Touch devices, which was ultimately declared as discontinued in 2012.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, David Wang under his company Corellium released Project Sandcastle which made Android run on the iPhone 7.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Internally, Android identifies each supported device by its **device codename**, a short string, which may or may not be similar to the model name used in marketing the device.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] For example, the device codename of the Pixel smartphone is *sailfish*.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is usually not visible to the end user, but is important for determining compatibility with modified Android versions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] It is sometimes also mentioned in articles discussing a device, because it allows to distinguish different hardware variants of a device, even if the manufacturer offers them under the same name.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is available to running applications under `android.os.Build.DEVICE`.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Google launched the Android Partner Vulnerability Initiative to improve the security of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] They also formed an Android security team.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Research from security company Trend Micro lists premium service abuse as the most common type of Android malware, where text messages are sent from infected phones to premium-rate telephone numbers without the consent or even knowledge of the user.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Other malware displays unwanted and intrusive advertisements on the device, or sends personal information to unauthorised third parties.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains that dangerous malware is actually extremely rare, and a survey conducted by F-Secure showed that only 0.5% of Android malware reported had come from the Google Play store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Analysis of data traffic by popular smartphones running variants of Android found substantial by-default data collection and sharing with no opt-out by this pre-installed software.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Both of these issues are not addressed or cannot be addressed by security patches.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] They were reportedly able to read almost all smartphone information, including SMS, location, emails, and notes.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] GCHQ has, according to *The Guardian*, a wiki-style guide of different apps and advertising networks, and the different data that can be siphoned from each.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Later that week, the Finnish Angry Birds developer Rovio announced that it was reconsidering its relationships with its advertising platforms in the light of these revelations, and called upon the wider industry to do the same.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The documents revealed a further effort by the intelligence agencies to intercept Google Maps searches and queries submitted from Android and other smartphones to collect location information in bulk.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Leaked documents codenamed Vault 7 and dated from 2013 to 2016, detail the capabilities of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, including the ability to compromise the operating systems of most smartphones (including Android).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2015, Google announced that devices in the Google Nexus series would begin to receive monthly security patches.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Ron Amadeo of *Ars Technica* wrote also in August 2015 that "Android was originally designed, above all else, to be widely adopted.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As such, security has become a big issue.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android still uses a software update chain-of-command designed back when the Android ecosystem had zero devices to update, and it just doesn't work".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Following news of Google's monthly schedule, some manufacturers, including Samsung and LG, promised to issue monthly security updates, but, as noted by Jerry Hildenbrand in *Android Central* in February 2016, "instead we got a few updates on specific versions of a small handful of models.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] They also wrote that "About half of devices in use at the end of 2016 had not received a platform security update in the previous year", stating that their work would continue to focus on streamlining the security updates program for easier deployment by manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, in a comment to *TechCrunch*, Ludwig stated that the wait time for security updates had been reduced from "six to nine weeks down to just a few days", with 78% of flagship devices in North America being up-to-date on security at the end of 2016.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-priced devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, the open-source nature of Android allows security contractors to take existing devices and adapt them for highly secure uses.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] For example, Samsung has worked with General Dynamics through their Open Kernel Labs acquisition to rebuild *Jelly Bean* on top of their hardened microvisor for the "Knox" project.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android smartphones have the ability to report the location of Wi-Fi access points, encountered as phone users move around, to build databases containing the physical locations of hundreds of millions of such access points.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] These databases form electronic maps to locate smartphones, allowing them to run apps like Foursquare, Google Latitude, Facebook Places, and to deliver location-based ads.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Third party monitoring software such as TaintDroid, an academic research-funded project, can, in some cases, detect when personal information is being sent from applications to remote servers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2018, Norwegian security firm Promon has unearthed a serious Android security hole which can be exploited to steal login credentials, access messages, and track location, which could be found in all versions of Android, including Android 10.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The vulnerability came by exploiting a bug in the multitasking system enabling a malicious app to overlay legitimate apps with fake login screens that users are not aware of when handing in security credentials.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Users can also be tricked into granting additional permissions to the malicious apps, which later enable them to perform various nefarious activities, including intercepting texts or calls and stealing banking credentials.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] *Avast Threat Labs* also discovered that many pre-installed apps on several hundred new Android devices contain dangerous malware and adware.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Some of the preinstalled malware can commit ad fraud or even take over its host device.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, the Which? watchdog reported that more than a billion Android devices released in 2012 or earlier, which was 40% of Android devices worldwide, were at risk of being hacked.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This conclusion stemmed from the fact that no security updates were issued for the Android versions below 7.0 in 2019.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Which? collaborated with the AV Comparatives anti-virus lab to infect five phone models with malware, and it succeeded in each case.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google refused to comment on the watchdog's speculations.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] On August 5, 2020, Twitter published a blog urging its users to update their applications to the latest version with regards to a security concern that allowed others to access direct messages.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] A hacker could easily use the "Android system permissions" to fetch the account credentials in order to do so.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The security issue is only with Android 8 (Android Oreo) and Android 9 (Android Pie).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Twitter confirmed that updating the app will restrict such practices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android applications run in a sandbox, an isolated area of the system that does not have access to the rest of the system's resources, unless access permissions are explicitly granted by the user when the application is installed, however this may not be possible for pre-installed apps.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] It is not possible, for example, to turn off the microphone access of the pre-installed camera app without disabling the camera completely.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This is valid also in Android versions 7 and 8.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Since February 2012, Google has used its Google Bouncer malware scanner to watch over and scan apps available in the Google Play store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] A "Verify Apps" feature was introduced in November 2012, as part of the Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean" operating system version, to scan all apps, both from Google Play and from third-party sources, for malicious behaviour.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Originally only doing so during installation, Verify Apps received an update in 2014 to "constantly" scan apps, and in 2017 the feature was made visible to users through a menu in Settings.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In former Android versions, before installing an application, the Google Play store displayed a list of the requirements an app needs to function.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] After reviewing these permissions, the user could choose to accept or refuse them, installing the application only if they accepted.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 6.0 "Marshmallow", the permissions system was changed; apps are no longer automatically granted all of their specified permissions at installation time.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] An opt-in system is used instead, in which users are prompted to grant or deny individual permissions to an app when they are needed for the first time.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Applications remember the grants, which can be revoked by the user at any time.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Pre-installed apps, however, are not always part of this approach.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In some cases it may not be possible to deny certain permissions to pre-installed apps, nor be possible to disable them.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The Google Play Services app cannot be uninstalled, nor disabled.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Any force stop attempt results in the app restarting itself.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The new permissions model is used only by applications developed for Marshmallow using its software development kit (SDK), and older apps will continue to use the previous all-or-nothing approach.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Permissions can still be revoked for those apps, though this might prevent them from working properly, and a warning is displayed to that effect.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In September 2014, Jason Nova of *Android Authority* reported on a study by the German security company Fraunhofer AISEC in antivirus software and malware threats on Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Nova wrote that "The Android operating system deals with software packages by sandboxing them; this does not allow applications to list the directory contents of other apps to keep the system safe.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] By not allowing the antivirus to list the directories of other apps after installation, applications that show no inherent suspicious behavior when downloaded are cleared as safe.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] If then later on parts of the app are activated that turn out to be malicious, the antivirus will have no way to know since it is inside the app and out of the antivirus' jurisdiction".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2013, Google announced Android Device Manager (renamed Find My Device in May 2017), a service that allows users to remotely track, locate, and wipe their Android device, with an Android app for the service released in December.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2016, Google introduced a Trusted Contacts app, letting users request location-tracking of loved ones during emergencies.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Trusted Contacts was shut down and the location-sharing feature rolled into Google Maps.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] On October 8, 2018, Google announced new Google Play store requirements to combat oversharing of potentially sensitive information, including call and text logs.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The issue stems from the fact that many apps request permissions to access users' personal information, even if this information is not needed for the app to function, and some users unquestionably grant these permissions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Alternatively, a permission might be listed in the app manifest as required (as opposed to optional) and the app would not install unless user grants the permission; users can withdraw any, even required, permissions from any app in the device settings after app installation, but few users do this.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google promised to work with developers and create exceptions if their apps require phone or SMS permissions for core functionality.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The enforcement of this policy began on January 6, 2019, 90 days after its announcement.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, Google announced a new "target API level requirement" (`targetSdkVersion` in manifest) of at least Android 8.0 (API level 26) for all new apps and app updates.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The API level requirement was intended to combat the practice of app developers bypassing some permission screens by specifying early Android versions that had a coarser permission model.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The Android Open Source Project implements a verified boot chain with intentions to verify that executed code, such as the kernel or bootloader, comes from an official source instead of a malicious actor.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This implementation establishes a full chain of trust, as it initially starts at a hardware level.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Subsequently, the boot loader is verified and system partitions such as `system` and `vendor` are checked for integrity.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, this process verifies that a previous version of Android has not been installed.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This effectively provides rollback protection, which mitigates exploits that are similar to a downgrade attack.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android (all supported versions, as far back as version 4.4 of the Android Open Source Project) has the option to provide a verified boot chain with `dm-verity`.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This is a feature in the Linux kernel that allows for transparent integrity checking of block devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This feature is designed to mitigate persistent rootkits.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Dependence on proprietary Google Play Services and customizations added on top of the operating system by vendors who license Android from Google is causing privacy concerns.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French CNIL for a lack of information regarding their users.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Two years later, in 2021, researcher Douglas Leith, using a sort of data interception, showed that several data are sent from Android device to Google's servers, even when the phone is sleeping (IDLE) with no Google account registered into it.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Several Google applications send data, such as Chrome, Message or Docs, however YouTube is the only one to add a unique identifier data.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Leith showed that an Android phone sent various data related to communications, including phone and text messages to Google.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Timestamp, sender and receiver, plus several other data, are sent to Google Play Services infrastructure, even if the "Usage and Diag" feature is disabled.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Those data are marked with a Unique Identifier of an Android device, and do not comply with GDPR.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Google was sanctioned A$60 Million (US$40 million) by the Federal Court of Australia for misleading consumers about Google's collection of location data from Android phones.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The ACCC estimates that around 1.3 million Australian Google account owners were impacted by this design.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google has since taken remedial steps to address the behavior.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] A similar case to the 2019 French case regarding location tracking, was brought in the U.S. in a privacy lawsuit filed by a coalition of attorneys general from 40 U.S. states.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] A penalty of USD 391 Million was agreed between Google and the DoJ.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The New York Times released at that time a long-term investigation about those privacy concerns.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Android devices, particularly low-end and mid-range models, have been criticized for their short software support lifespans.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in the 2010s, many users found that their devices received only one or two major updates and a limited number of security patches.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This lack of long-term support stemmed from manufacturers' unwillingness to invest in costly software upgrades, which were often tied to contractual agreements with chipset suppliers like Qualcomm.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android developed a reputation for rapid device obsolescence.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] To address this concern, Google introduced Project Treble, a framework designed to streamline the development and deployment of Android updates via Google Play Services, reducing manufacturers' involvement in the update process.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, for many devices, significant improvements were still limited by the chipset manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Fairphone, a company focused on sustainability, explained that its inability to extend software support was due to Qualcomm's policies rather than its own.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Apple executives also highlighted Android's fragmented update ecosystem in their critiques of the platform, while quietly admitting that Qualcomm had also made it difficult for them to offer updates to the iPhone.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this problem, several community-driven initiatives emerged to provide alternative operating systems for unsupported devices including LineageOS, Sailfish OS, Ubuntu Touch, and PostmarketOS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in 2022, Samsung, the largest Android smartphone manufacturer, announced extended software support from previous two years, first to four years, followed by five years in 2023 and six years in 2024.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Shortly thereafter, Qualcomm followed suit, offering extending support timelines for OEM building phones with its chipsets, first to seven years in 2024, followed by eight years in 2025.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] However, the support commitment was only for its most powerful chipsets, and did not make a similar commitment for chipsets used in low-end and mid-range phones.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] These changes bring Samsung and potentially some Qualcomm-powered devices closer to competing platforms, such as Apple, whose iPhones have received four to eight years of support.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] In 2025, Google announced that all developers must register under its developer program in order to distribute applications on certified Android phones, whether it is done through the Play Store, sideloaded APKs, or third-party stores like F-Droid, citing security reasons.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] This measure will be effective starting September 2026.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] The measure will not directly affect degoogled custom ROMs, such as GrapheneOS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] Google has faced a backlash by experts, developers, activists, lawyers and other groups, which founded the Keep Android Open initiative to raise awareness and signed an open letter urging Google to rescind the policy.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] They argue that Google will become a gatekeeper as it will be able to decide which apps can be installed and which others will not, provided that "sideloading" will be considerably tampered by the measure (at least 9 steps needed and it would imply waiting 24 hours before an install).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p02] They also criticize that it creates "an ever-expanding pathway to internet censorship" alleging more centralization of power.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The source code for Android is open-source: it is developed in private by Google, with the source code released publicly when a new version of Android is released.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google publishes most of the code (including network and telephony stacks) under the non-copyleft Apache License version 2.0. which allows modification and redistribution.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The license does not grant rights to the "Android" trademark, so device manufacturers and wireless carriers have to license it from Google under individual contracts.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Associated Linux kernel changes are released under the copyleft GNU General Public License version 2, developed by the Open Handset Alliance, with the source code publicly available at all times.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The only Android release which was not immediately made available as source code was the tablet-only 3.0 *Honeycomb* release.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The reason, according to Andy Rubin in an official Android blog post, was because *Honeycomb* was rushed for production of the Motorola Xoom, and they did not want third parties creating a "really bad user experience" by attempting to put onto smartphones a version of Android intended for tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] These applications must be licensed from Google by device makers, and can only be shipped on devices which meet its compatibility guidelines and other requirements.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Custom, certified distributions of Android produced by manufacturers (such as Samsung Experience) may also replace certain stock Android apps with their own proprietary variants and add additional software not included in the stock Android operating system.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] With the advent of the Google Pixel line of devices, Google itself has also made specific Android features timed or permanent exclusives to the Pixel series.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] There may also be "binary blob" drivers required for certain hardware components in the device.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The best known fully open source Android services are the LineageOS distribution and MicroG which acts as an open source replacement of Google Play Services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In both cases, the use of closed-source software causes the system to become vulnerable to backdoors.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] It has been argued that because developers are often required to purchase the Google-branded Android license, this has turned the theoretically open system into a freemium service.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google licenses their Google Mobile Services software, along with the Android trademarks, only to hardware manufacturers for devices that meet Google's compatibility standards specified in the Android Compatibility Program document.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Thus, forks of Android that make major changes to the operating system itself do not include any of Google's non-free components, stay incompatible with applications that require them, and must ship with an alternative software marketplace in lieu of Google Play Store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] A prominent example of such an Android fork is Amazon's Fire OS, which is used on the Kindle Fire line of tablets, and oriented toward Amazon services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The shipment of Android devices without GMS is also common in mainland China, as Google does not do business there.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, Google also began to require that all Android devices which license the Google Mobile Services software display a prominent "Powered by Android" logo on their boot screens.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In March 2018, it was reported that Google had begun to block "uncertified" Android devices from using Google Mobile Services software, and display a warning indicating that "the device manufacturer has preloaded Google apps and services without certification from Google".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Users of custom ROMs can register their device ID to their Google account to remove this block.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Moreover, open-source variants of some applications also exclude functions that are present in their non-free versions.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Apps that do not use Google components would also be at a functional disadvantage, as they can only use APIs contained within the OS itself.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In turn, third-party apps may have dependencies on Google Play Services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Alibaba Group defended the allegations, arguing that the OS was a distinct platform from Android (primarily using HTML5 apps), but incorporated portions of Android's platform to allow backwards compatibility with third-party Android software.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Indeed, the devices did ship with an application store which offered Android apps; however, the majority of them were pirated.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android received a lukewarm reaction when it was unveiled in 2007.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Although analysts were impressed with the respected technology companies that had partnered with Google to form the Open Handset Alliance, it was unclear whether mobile phone manufacturers would be willing to replace their existing operating systems with Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The idea of an open-source, Linux-based development platform sparked interest, but there were additional worries about Android facing strong competition from established players in the smartphone market, such as Nokia and Microsoft, and rival Linux mobile operating systems that were in development.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Since then Android has grown to become the most widely used smartphone operating system and "one of the fastest mobile experiences available".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As a result, it has been described by technology website *Ars Technica* as "practically the default operating system for launching new hardware" for companies without their own mobile platforms.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This openness and flexibility is also present at the level of the end user: Android allows extensive customisation of devices by their owners and apps are freely available from non-Google app stores and third party websites.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] These have been cited as among the main advantages of Android phones over others.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Despite Android's popularity, including an activation rate three times that of iOS, there have been reports that Google has not been able to leverage their other products and web services successfully to turn Android into the money maker that analysts had expected.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, in an effort to improve prominence of the Android brand, Google began to require that devices featuring its proprietary components display an Android logo on the boot screen.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] For example, according to data from OpenSignal in July 2013, there were 11,868 models of Android devices, numerous screen sizes and eight Android OS versions simultaneously in use, while the large majority of iOS users have upgraded to the latest iteration of that OS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Critics such as *Apple Insider* have asserted that fragmentation via hardware and software pushed Android's growth through large volumes of low end, budget-priced devices running older versions of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] They maintain this forces Android developers to write for the "lowest common denominator" to reach as many users as possible, who have too little incentive to make use of the latest hardware or software features only available on a smaller percentage of devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] However, OpenSignal, who develops both Android and iOS apps, concluded that although fragmentation can make development trickier, Android's wider global reach also increases the potential reward.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the largest mobile OS with 76% market share as of Q1 2025.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most used operating system on phones in many countries, with some countries, such as India, having over 96% market share.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, usage is more even, as iOS is a bit more popular globally.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Research company Canalys estimated in the second quarter of 2009, that Android had a 2.8% share of worldwide smartphone shipments.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] By May 2010, Android had a 10% worldwide smartphone market share, overtaking Windows Mobile, whilst in the US Android held a 28% share, overtaking iPhone OS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] By the fourth quarter of 2010, its worldwide share had grown to 33% of the market becoming the top-selling smartphone platform, overtaking Symbian.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In the US it became the top-selling platform in April 2011, overtaking BlackBerry OS with a 31.2% smartphone share, according to *comScore*.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2011, Gartner estimated that more than half (52.5%) of the smartphone sales belonged to Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2012 Android had a 75% share of the global smartphone market according to the research firm IDC.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2011, Google said that 550,000 Android devices were being activated every day, up from 400,000 per day in May, and more than 100 million devices had been activated with 4.4% growth per week.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2012, 500 million devices had been activated with 1.3 million activations per day.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2013, at Google I/O, Sundar Pichai announced that 900 million Android devices had been activated.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android market share varies by location.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2012, "mobile subscribers aged 13+" in the United States using Android were up to 52%, and rose to 90% in China.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] During the third quarter of 2012, Android's worldwide smartphone shipment market share was 75%, with 750 million devices activated in total.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2013, Android had 1.5 million activations per day.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As of May 2013, 48 billion application ("app") installation have been performed from the Google Play store, and by September 2013, one billion Android devices had been activated.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As of August 2020, the Google Play store had over 3 million Android applications published, and as of May 2016, apps had been downloaded more than 65 billion times.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The operating system's success has made it a target for patent litigation as part of the so-called "smartphone wars" between technology companies.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android devices account for more than half of smartphone sales in most markets, including the US, while "only in Japan was Apple on top" (September–November 2013 numbers).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] At the end of 2013, over 1.5 billion Android smartphones had been sold in the four years since 2010, making Android the most sold phone and tablet OS.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Three billion Android smartphones were estimated to be sold by the end of 2014 (including previous years).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to Gartner research company, Android-based devices outsold all contenders, every year since 2012.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, it outsold Windows 2.8:1 or by 573 million.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As of 2015, Android has the largest installed base of all operating systems; Since 2013, devices running it also sell more than Windows, iOS and Mac OS X devices combined.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter, which tracks only the use for browsing the web, Android is the most popular mobile operating system since August 2013.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most popular operating system for web browsing in India and several other countries (e.g. virtually all of Asia, with Japan and North Korea exceptions).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Gartner expected the whole mobile phone market to "reach two billion units in 2016", including Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to a Statistica's estimate, Android smartphones had an installed base of 1.8 billion units in 2015, which was 76% of the estimated total number of smartphones worldwide.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android has the largest installed base of any mobile operating system and, since 2013, the highest-selling operating system overall with sales in 2012, 2013 and 2014 close to the installed base of all PCs.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In the second quarter of 2014, Android's share of the global smartphone shipment market was 84.7%, a new record.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This had grown to 87.5% worldwide market share by the third quarter of 2016, leaving main competitor iOS with 12.1% market share.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to an April 2017 StatCounter report, Android overtook Microsoft Windows to become the most popular operating system for total Internet usage.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] It has maintained the plurality since then.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2015, Google announced that Android had 1.4 billion monthly active users.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This changed to 2 billion monthly active users in May 2017.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Despite its success on smartphones, initially Android tablet adoption was slow, then later caught up with the iPad, in most countries.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] One of the main causes was the chicken or the egg situation where consumers were hesitant to buy an Android tablet due to a lack of high quality tablet applications, but developers were hesitant to spend time and resources developing tablet applications until there was a significant market for them.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The content and app "ecosystem" proved more important than hardware specs as the selling point for tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Due to the lack of Android tablet-specific applications in 2011, early Android tablets had to make do with existing smartphone applications that were ill-suited to larger screen sizes, whereas the dominance of Apple's iPad was reinforced by the large number of tablet-specific iOS applications.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Despite app support in its infancy, a considerable number of Android tablets, like the Barnes & Noble Nook (alongside those using other operating systems, such as the HP TouchPad and BlackBerry PlayBook) were rushed out to market in an attempt to capitalize on the success of the iPad.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This approach, such as with the Dell Streak, failed to gain market traction with consumers as well as damaging the early reputation of Android tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Furthermore, several Android tablets such as the Motorola Xoom were priced the same or higher than the iPad, which hurt sales.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] An exception was the Amazon Kindle Fire, which relied upon lower pricing as well as access to Amazon's ecosystem of applications and content.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This began to change in 2012, with the release of the affordable Nexus 7 and a push by Google for developers to write better tablet applications.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to International Data Corporation, shipments of Android-powered tablets surpassed iPads in Q3 2012.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As of the end of 2013, over 191.6 million Android tablets had sold in three years since 2011.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] This made Android tablets the most-sold type of tablet in 2013, surpassing iPads in the second quarter of 2013.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter's web use statistics, as of 2020, Android tablets represent the majority of tablet devices used in Africa (70%), South America (65%), while less than half elsewhere, e.g.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] There are countries on all continents where Android tablets are the majority, for example, Mexico.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] India, and in Europe, with some notable exceptions such as the US (iPadOS 57%), and in China (iPadOS 53%)).
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Of all operating systems Android is first at 37%, followed by Windows at 28%, then iOS/iPadOS at 18%.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The latest version Android 16 is the most popular Android version on smartphones and Android 14 on tablets.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] As of April 2026, the latest version Android 16 is most popular Android version on smartphones at 22%, followed by Android 15 (at 19%, down from 30% peak), 13, 14, 12 and 11.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android is more used than iOS is virtually all countries, with few exceptions such as iOS has a 58% share in the US.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android 16 is the most-used version in e.g.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] US, Europe, China, and Japan and Android 15 in India.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 69%, the rest of users are not supported with security updates; with recently supported Android 12 (last security updates in 2025), use is at 79%.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, Android 14 is the most popular version overall (also in e.g.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] India, Russia, Canada, Australia, Europe and South America), at 19%.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 48.2% on Android tablets, and with Android 12, until recently supported, at 56.7%.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The usage share varies a lot by country.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] 73% of US users use insecure Android tablets, and 78% of UK users, and the very old Android 9.0 Pie is still the most commonly used tablet version in both countries.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Paid Android applications in the past were simple to pirate.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In a May 2012 interview with *Eurogamer*, the developers of *Football Manager* stated that the ratio of pirated players vs legitimate players was 9:1 for their game *Football Manager Handheld*.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] However, not every developer agreed that piracy rates were an issue; for example, in July 2012 the developers of the game *Wind-up Knight* said that piracy levels of their game were only 12%, and most of the piracy came from China, where people cannot purchase apps from Google Play.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2010, Google released a tool for validating authorized purchases for use within apps, but developers complained that this was insufficient and trivial to crack.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google responded that the tool, especially its initial release, was intended as a sample framework for developers to modify and build upon depending on their needs, not as a finished piracy solution.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android "Jelly Bean" introduced the ability for paid applications to be encrypted, so that they may work only on the device for which they were purchased.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android has been the subject of various cases of patent, copyright, and antitrust litigation.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On August 12, 2010, Oracle sued Google over claimed infringement of copyrights and patents related to the Java programming language.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Oracle originally sought damages up to $6.1 billion, but this valuation was rejected by a United States federal judge who asked Oracle to revise the estimate.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In response, Google submitted multiple lines of defense, counterclaiming that Android did not infringe on Oracle's patents or copyright, that Oracle's patents were invalid, and several other defenses.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] They said that Android's Java runtime environment is based on Apache Harmony, a clean room implementation of the Java class libraries, and an independently developed virtual machine called Dalvik.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2012, the jury in this case found that Google did not infringe on Oracle's patents, and the trial judge ruled that the structure of the Java APIs used by Google was not copyrightable.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The parties agreed to zero dollars in statutory damages for a small amount of copied code.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On May 9, 2014, the Federal Circuit partially reversed the district court ruling, ruling in Oracle's favor on the copyrightability issue, and remanding the issue of fair use to the district court.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2015, Google announced that the next major release of Android (Android Nougat) would switch to OpenJDK, which is the official open-source implementation of the Java platform, instead of using the now-discontinued Apache Harmony project as its runtime.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Code reflecting this change was also posted to the AOSP source repository.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In its announcement, Google claimed this was part of an effort to create a "common code base" between Java on Android and other platforms.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In June 2016, a United States federal court ruled in favor of Google, stating that its use of the APIs was fair use.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2021, the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that Google's use of the Java APIs was within the bounds of fair use, reversing the Federal Circuit Appeals Court ruling and remanding the case for further hearing.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The majority opinion began with the assumption that the APIs may be copyrightable, and thus proceeded with a review of the factors that contributed to fair use.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In addition to lawsuits against Google directly, various proxy wars have been waged against Android indirectly by targeting manufacturers of Android devices, with the effect of discouraging manufacturers from adopting the platform by increasing the costs of bringing an Android device to market.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Both Apple and Microsoft have sued several manufacturers for patent infringement, with Apple's legal action against Samsung being a particularly high-profile case.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In January 2012, Microsoft said they had signed patent license agreements with eleven Android device manufacturers, whose products account for "70 percent of all Android smartphones" sold in the US and 55% of the worldwide revenue for Android devices.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Samsung's patent settlement with Microsoft included an agreement to allocate more resources to developing and marketing phones running Microsoft's Windows Phone operating system.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Microsoft has also tied its own Android software to patent licenses, requiring the bundling of Microsoft Office Mobile and Skype applications on Android devices to subsidize the licensing fees, while at the same time helping to promote its software lines.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google has publicly expressed its frustration for the current patent landscape in the United States, accusing Apple, Oracle and Microsoft of trying to take down Android through patent litigation, rather than innovating and competing with better products and services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2011, Google purchased Motorola Mobility for US$12.5 billion, which was viewed in part as a defensive measure to protect Android, since Motorola Mobility held more than 17,000 patents.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2011, Google bought over a thousand patents from IBM.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, FairSearch, a lobbying organization supported by Microsoft, Oracle and others, filed a complaint regarding Android with the European Commission, alleging that its free-of-charge distribution model constituted anti-competitive predatory pricing.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The Free Software Foundation Europe, whose donors include Google, disputed the Fairsearch allegations.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2016, Google was fined US$6.75 million by the Russian Federal Antimonopoly Service (FAS) under similar allegations by Yandex.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The EU fined Google for €4.3 billion (about US$5 billion) and required the company to end this conduct within 90 days.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google filed its appeal of the ruling in October 2018, though will not ask for any interim measures to delay the onset of conduct requirements.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On October 16, 2018, Google announced that it would change its distribution model for Google Mobile Services in the EU, since part of its revenues streams for Android which came through use of Google Search and Chrome were now prohibited by the EU's ruling.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] While the core Android system remains free, OEMs in Europe would be required to purchase a paid license to the core suite of Google applications, such as Gmail, Google Maps and the Google Play Store.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google Search will be licensed separately, with an option to include Google Chrome at no additional cost atop Search.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] European OEMs can bundle third-party alternatives on phones and devices sold to customers, if they so choose.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] OEMs will no longer be barred from selling any device running incompatible versions of Android in Europe.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Turkey's competition authority began investigating the default Android search engine in 2017, leading to a US$17.4 million fine in September 2018 and a fine of 0.05 percent of Google's revenue per day in November 2019 when Google did not meet the requirements.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2019, Google stopped issuing licenses for new Android phone models sold in Turkey.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2021, the Fair Trade Commission (South Korea) fined Google $177 million for restricting manufacturers, such as Samsung Electronics, from using modified versions of Android.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2025, the Competition Commission of India charged Google for "mandatory preinstallation of Google Play Store and other applications" on Android TV.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google settled, unbundling the services and paying a $2.38 million fine.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google has developed several variations of Android for specific use cases, including Android Wear, later renamed Wear OS, for wearable devices such as wrist watches, Android TV for televisions, Android Things for smart or Internet of things devices and Android Automotive for cars.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, by providing infrastructure that combines dedicated hardware and dedicated applications running on regular Android, Google have opened up the platform for its use in particular usage scenarios, such as the Android Auto app for cars, and Daydream, a Virtual Reality platform.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, Android has been installed and run on a variety of less-technical objects, including calculators, single-board computers, feature phones, electronic dictionaries, alarm clocks, refrigerators, landline telephones, coffee machines, bicycles, and mirrors.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Ouya, a video game console running Android, became one of the most successful Kickstarter campaigns, crowdfunding US$8.5m for its development, and was later followed by other Android-based consoles, such as Nvidia's Shield Portable – an Android device in a video game controller form factor.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2011, Google demonstrated "Android@Home", a home automation technology which uses Android to control a range of household devices including light switches, power sockets and thermostats.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Prototype light bulbs were announced that could be controlled from an Android phone or tablet, but Android head Andy Rubin was cautious to note that "turning a lightbulb on and off is nothing new", pointing to numerous failed home automation services.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Google, he said, was thinking more ambitiously and the intention was to use their position as a cloud services provider to bring Google products into customers' homes.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Parrot unveiled an Android-based car stereo system known as Asteroid in 2011, followed by a successor, the touchscreen-based Asteroid Smart, in 2012.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, Clarion released its own Android-based car stereo, the AX1.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Android comes preinstalled on a few laptops (a similar functionality of running Android applications is also available in Google's ChromeOS) and can also be installed on personal computers by end users.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] On those platforms Android provides additional functionality for physical keyboards and mice, together with the "Alt-Tab" key combination for switching applications quickly with a keyboard.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2014, one reviewer commented that Android's notification system is "vastly more complete and robust than in most environments" and that Android is "absolutely usable" as one's primary desktop operating system.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In October 2015, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Android will serve as Google's future main laptop operating system, with the plan to fold ChromeOS into it by 2017.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] That is unlike Android where support is shorter with "EOL dates [being..] at least 3 years [into the future] for Android tablets for education".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] At Google I/O in May 2016, Google announced Daydream, a virtual reality platform that relied on a smartphone and provided VR capabilities through a virtual reality headset and controller designed by Google itself.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] However, this did not catch on and was discontinued in 2019.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The mascot of Android is a green android robot, as related to the software's name.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Although it had no official name for a long time, the Android team at Google reportedly call it "Bugdroid".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] In 2024, a Google blog post revealed its official name, "The Bot".
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] It was designed by then-Google graphic designer Irina Blok on November 5, 2007, when Android was announced.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Contrary to reports that she was tasked with a project to create an icon, Blok confirmed in an interview that she independently developed it and made it open source.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] The robot design was initially not presented to Google, but it quickly became commonplace in the Android development team, with various variations of it created by the developers there who liked the figure, as it was free under a Creative Commons license.
[src:board-support-package/android-operating-system-p03] Its popularity amongst the development team eventually led to Google adopting it as an official icon as part of the Android logo when it launched to consumers in 2008.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:board-support-package/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language usually has one statement per machine code instruction (1:1), but constants, comments, assembler directives, symbolic labels of, e.g., memory locations, registers, and macros are generally also supported.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The first assembly code in which a language is used to represent machine code instructions is found in Kathleen and Andrew Donald Booth's 1947 work, *Coding for A.R.C.*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly code is converted into executable machine code by a utility program referred to as an *assembler*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The term "assembler" is generally attributed to Wilkes, Wheeler and Gill in their 1951 book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer*, who, however, used the term to mean "a program that assembles another program consisting of several sections into a single program".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The conversion process is referred to as *assembly*, as in *assembling* the source code.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The computational step when an assembler is processing a program is called *assembly time*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Because assembly depends on the machine code instructions, each assembly language is specific to a particular computer architecture such as x86 or ARM.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes there is more than one assembler for the same architecture, and sometimes an assembler is specific to an operating system or to particular operating systems.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Most assembly languages do not provide specific syntax for operating system calls, and most assembly languages can be used universally with any operating system, as the language provides access to all the real capabilities of the processor, upon which all system call mechanisms ultimately rest.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In contrast to assembly languages, most high-level programming languages are generally portable across multiple architectures but require interpreting or compiling, much more complicated tasks than assembling.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In the first decades of computing, it was commonplace for both systems programming and application programming to take place entirely in assembly language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] While still irreplaceable for some purposes, the majority of programming is now conducted in higher-level interpreted and compiled languages.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In "No Silver Bullet", Fred Brooks summarised the effects of the switch away from assembly language programming: "Surely the most powerful stroke for software productivity, reliability, and simplicity has been the progressive use of high-level languages for programming.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Today, it is typical to use small amounts of assembly language code within larger systems implemented in a higher-level language, for performance reasons or to interact directly with hardware in ways unsupported by the higher-level language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For instance, just under 2% of version 4.9 of the Linux kernel source code is written in assembly; more than 97% is written in C.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language uses mnemonic symbols to represent low-level machine instructions (opcodes), directives, and usually architectural registers and flags.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some of the mnemonics may be built-in and some user-defined.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Many operations require one or more operands in order to form a complete instruction.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers permit named constants, registers, and labels for program and memory locations, and can calculate expressions for operands.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Thus, programmers are freed from tedious repetitive calculations and assembler programs are much more readable than machine code.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Depending on the architecture, these elements may also be combined for specific instructions or addressing modes using offsets or other data as well as fixed addresses.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers offer additional mechanisms to facilitate program development, to control the assembly process, and to aid debugging.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some are column oriented, with specific fields in specific columns; this was very common for machines using punched cards in the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers have free-form syntax, with fields separated by delimiters, e.g., punctuation, white space.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers are hybrid, with, e.g., labels, in a specific column and other fields separated by delimiters; this became more common than column-oriented syntax in the 1960s.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] An **assembler** program creates object code by translating combinations of mnemonics and syntax for operations and addressing modes into their numerical equivalents.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This representation typically includes an *operation code* ("opcode") as well as other control bits and data.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The assembler also calculates constant expressions and resolves symbolic names for memory locations and other entities.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The use of symbolic references is a key feature of assemblers, saving tedious calculations and manual address updates after program modifications.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Most assemblers also include macro facilities for performing textual substitution – e.g., to generate common short sequences of instructions as inline, instead of *called* subroutines.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers may also be able to perform some simple types of instruction set-specific optimizations.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] One concrete example of this may be the ubiquitous x86 assemblers from various vendors.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Called jump-sizing, most of them are able to perform jump-instruction replacements (long jumps replaced by short or relative jumps) in any number of passes, on request.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Others may even do simple rearrangement or insertion of instructions, such as some assemblers for RISC architectures that can help optimize a sensible instruction scheduling to exploit the CPU pipeline as efficiently as possible.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assemblers have been available since the 1950s, as the first step above machine language and before high-level programming languages such as Fortran, Algol, COBOL and Lisp.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There have also been several classes of translators and semi-automatic code generators with properties similar to both assembly and high-level languages, with Speedcode as perhaps one of the better-known examples.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There may be several assemblers with different syntax for a particular CPU or instruction set architecture.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For instance, an instruction to add memory data to a register in a x86-family processor might be `add eax,[ebx]`, in original *Intel syntax*, whereas this would be written `addl (%ebx),%eax` in the *AT&T syntax* used by the GNU Assembler.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Despite different appearances, different syntactic forms generally generate the same numeric machine code.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] A single assembler may also have different modes in order to support variations in syntactic forms as well as their exact semantic interpretations (such as FASM-syntax, TASM-syntax, ideal mode, etc., in the special case of x86 assembly programming).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There are two types of assemblers based on how many passes through the source are needed (how many times the assembler reads the source) to produce the object file.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In both cases, the assembler must be able to determine the size of each instruction on the initial passes in order to calculate the addresses of subsequent symbols.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In an assembler with peephole optimization, addresses may be recalculated between passes to allow replacing pessimistic code with code tailored to the exact distance from the target.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The original reason for the use of one-pass assemblers was memory size and speed of assembly – often a second pass would require storing the symbol table in memory (to handle forward references), rewinding and rereading the program source on tape, or rereading a deck of cards or punched paper tape.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Later computers with much larger memories (especially disc storage), had the space to perform all necessary processing without such re-reading.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The advantage of the multi-pass assembler is that the absence of errata makes the linking process (or the program load if the assembler directly produces executable code) faster.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] See Language design below for more details.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] A program written in assembly language consists of a series of mnemonic processor instructions and meta-statements (known variously as declarative operations, directives, pseudo-instructions, pseudo-operations and pseudo-ops), comments and data.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language instructions usually consist of an opcode mnemonic followed by an operand, which might be a list of data, arguments or parameters.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some instructions may be "implied", which means the data upon which the instruction operates is implicitly defined by the instruction itself—such an instruction does not take an operand.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The resulting statement is translated by an assembler into machine language instructions that can be loaded into memory and executed.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For example, the instruction below tells an x86/IA-32 processor to move an immediate 8-bit value into a register.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The binary code for this instruction is 10110 followed by a 3-bit identifier for which register to use.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The identifier for the *AL* register is 000, so the following machine code loads the *AL* register with the data 01100001.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This binary computer code can be made more human-readable by expressing it in hexadecimal as follows.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Here, `B0` means "Move a copy of the following value into *AL*", and `61` is a hexadecimal representation of the value 01100001, which is 97 in decimal.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language for the 8086 family provides the mnemonic MOV (an abbreviation of *move*) for instructions such as this, so the machine code above can be written as follows in assembly language, complete with an explanatory comment if required, after the semicolon.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This is much easier to read and to remember.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Other assemblers may use separate opcode mnemonics such as L for "move memory to register", ST for "move register to memory", LR for "move register to register", MVI for "move immediate operand to memory", etc.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] If the same mnemonic is used for different instructions, that means that the mnemonic corresponds to several different binary instruction codes, excluding data (e.g. the `61h` in this example), depending on the operands that follow the mnemonic.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For example, for the x86/IA-32 CPUs, the Intel assembly language syntax `MOV AL, AH` represents an instruction that moves the contents of register *AH* into register *AL*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The first byte, 88h, identifies a move between a byte-sized register and either another register or memory, and the second byte, E0h, is encoded (with three bit-fields) to specify that both operands are registers, the source is *AH*, and the destination is *AL*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In a case like this where the same mnemonic can represent more than one binary instruction, the assembler determines which instruction to generate by examining the operands.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In the first example, the operand `61h` is a valid hexadecimal numeric constant and is not a valid register name, so only the `B0` instruction can be applicable.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In the second example, the operand `AH` is a valid register name and not a valid numeric constant (hexadecimal, decimal, octal, or binary), so only the `88` instruction can be applicable.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages are always designed so that this sort of lack of ambiguity is universally enforced by their syntax.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For example, in the Intel x86 assembly language, a hexadecimal constant must start with a numeral digit, so that the hexadecimal number 'A' (equal to decimal ten) would be written as `0Ah` or `0AH`, not `AH`, specifically so that it cannot appear to be the name of register *AH*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Returning to the original example, while the x86 opcode 10110000 (`B0`) copies an 8-bit value into the *AL* register, 10110001 (`B1`) moves it into *CL* and 10110010 (`B2`) does so into *DL*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly language examples for these follow.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The syntax of MOV can also be more complex as the following examples show.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In each case, the MOV mnemonic is translated directly into one of the opcodes 88-8C, 8E, A0-A3, B0-BF, C6 or C7 by an assembler, and the programmer normally does not have to know or remember which.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] An assembler transforms assembly language into machine code, and the reverse can at least partially be achieved by a disassembler.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Unlike high-level languages, there is a one-to-one correspondence between many simple assembly statements and machine language instructions.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] However, in some cases, an assembler may provide *pseudoinstructions* (essentially macros) which expand into several machine language instructions to provide commonly needed functionality.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For example, for a machine that lacks a "branch if greater or equal" instruction, an assembler may provide a pseudoinstruction that expands to the machine's "set if less than" and "branch if zero (on the result of the set instruction)".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Most full-featured assemblers also provide a rich macro language (discussed below) which is used by vendors and programmers to generate more complex code and data sequences.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Likewise, since comments in the assembly language source file are ignored by the assembler and have no effect on the object code it generates, a disassembler is always completely unable to recover source comments.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Each computer architecture has its own machine language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Computers differ in the number and type of operations they support, in the different sizes and numbers of registers, and in the representations of data in storage.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] While most general-purpose computers are able to carry out essentially the same functionality, the ways they do so differ; the corresponding assembly languages reflect these differences.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Multiple sets of mnemonics or assembly-language syntax may exist for a single instruction set, typically instantiated in different assembler programs.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In these cases, the most popular one is usually that supplied by the CPU manufacturer and used in its documentation.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Two examples of CPUs that have two different sets of mnemonics are the Intel 8080 family and the Intel 8086/8088.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Because Intel claimed copyright on its assembly language mnemonics (on each page of their documentation published in the 1970s and early 1980s, at least), some companies that independently produced CPUs compatible with Intel instruction sets invented their own mnemonics.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The Zilog Z80 CPU, an enhancement of the Intel 8080A, supports all the 8080A instructions plus many more; Zilog invented an entirely new assembly language, not only for the new instructions but also for all of the 8080A instructions.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For example, where Intel uses the mnemonics *MOV*, *MVI*, *LDA*, *STA*, *LXI*, *LDAX*, *STAX*, *LHLD*, and *SHLD* for various data transfer instructions, the Z80 assembly language uses the mnemonic *LD* for all of them.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] A similar case is the NEC V20 and V30 CPUs, enhanced copies of the Intel 8086 and 8088, respectively.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Like Zilog with the Z80, NEC invented new mnemonics for all of the 8086 and 8088 instructions, to avoid accusations of infringement of Intel's copyright.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] "Hello, world!" can be printed using 32-bit assembly language for an x86 processor with little help from an operating system.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] "Call outchr" calls some mechanism that prints a character in AL to the console.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] A non zero-length string must be terminated with a byte of zero.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There is a large degree of diversity in the way the authors of assemblers categorize statements and in the nomenclature that they use.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In particular, some describe anything other than a machine mnemonic or extended mnemonic as a pseudo-operation (pseudo-op).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Instructions (statements) in assembly language are generally very simple, unlike those in high-level languages.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Generally, a mnemonic is a symbolic name for a single executable machine language instruction (an opcode), and there is at least one opcode mnemonic defined for each machine language instruction.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Each instruction typically consists of an *operation* or *opcode* plus zero or more *operands*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Most instructions refer to a single value or a pair of values.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Operands can be immediate (value coded in the instruction itself), registers specified in the instruction or implied, or the addresses of data located elsewhere in storage.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This is determined by the underlying processor architecture: the assembler merely reflects how this architecture works.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] *Extended mnemonics* are often used to specify a combination of an opcode with a specific operand, e.g., the System/360 assemblers use `B` as an extended mnemonic for `BC` with a mask of 15 and `NOP` ("NO OPeration" – do nothing for one step) for `BC` with a mask of 0.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers also support simple built-in macro-instructions that generate two or more machine instructions.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For instance, with some Z80 assemblers the instruction `ld hl,bc` is recognized to generate `ld l,c` followed by `ld h,b`.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] These are sometimes known as *pseudo-opcodes*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Mnemonics are arbitrary symbols; in 1985 the IEEE published Standard 694 for a uniform set of mnemonics to be used by all assemblers.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There are instructions used to define data elements to hold data and variables.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] They define the type of data, the length and the alignment of data.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] These instructions can also define whether the data is available to outside programs (programs assembled separately) or only to the program in which the data section is defined.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers classify these as pseudo-ops.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly directives, also called pseudo-opcodes, pseudo-operations or pseudo-ops, are commands given to an assembler "directing it to perform operations other than assembling instructions".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Directives affect how the assembler operates and "may affect the object code, the symbol table, the listing file, and the values of internal assembler parameters".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Sometimes the term *pseudo-opcode* is reserved for directives that generate object code, such as those that generate data.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The names of pseudo-ops often start with a dot to distinguish them from machine instructions.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Pseudo-ops can make the assembly of the program dependent on parameters input by a programmer, so that one program can be assembled in different ways, perhaps for different applications.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Or, a pseudo-op can be used to manipulate presentation of a program to make it easier to read and maintain.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Another common use of pseudo-ops is to reserve storage areas for run-time data and optionally initialize their contents to known values.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Symbolic assemblers let programmers associate arbitrary names (*labels* or *symbols*) with memory locations and various constants.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Usually, every constant and variable is given a name so instructions can reference those locations by name, thus promoting self-documenting code.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In executable code, the name of each subroutine is associated with its entry point, so any calls to a subroutine can use its name.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Inside subroutines, GOTO destinations are given labels.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers support *local symbols* which are often lexically distinct from normal symbols (e.g., the use of "10$" as a GOTO destination).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Some assemblers, such as NASM, provide flexible symbol management, letting programmers manage different namespaces, automatically calculate offsets within data structures, and assign labels that refer to literal values or the result of simple computations performed by the assembler.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Labels can also be used to initialize constants and variables with relocatable addresses.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembly languages, like most other computer languages, allow comments to be added to program source code that will be ignored during assembly.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Judicious commenting is essential in assembly language programs, as the meaning and purpose of a sequence of binary machine instructions can be difficult to determine.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The "raw" (uncommented) assembly language generated by compilers or disassemblers is quite difficult to read when changes must be made.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Many assemblers support *predefined macros*, and others support *programmer-defined* (and repeatedly re-definable) macros involving sequences of text lines in which variables and constants are embedded.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The macro definition is most commonly a mixture of assembler statements, e.g., directives, symbolic machine instructions, and templates for assembler statements.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This sequence of text lines may include opcodes or directives.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Once a macro has been defined its name may be used in place of a mnemonic.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] When the assembler processes such a statement, it replaces the statement with the text lines associated with that macro, then processes them as if they existed in the source code file (including, in some assemblers, expansion of any macros existing in the replacement text).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Macros in this sense date to IBM autocoders of the 1950s.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In assembly language, the term "macro" represents a more comprehensive concept than it does in some other contexts, such as the pre-processor in the C programming language, where its #define directive typically is used to create short single line macros.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembler macro instructions, like macros in PL/I and some other languages, can be lengthy "programs" by themselves, executed by interpretation by the assembler during assembly.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Since macros can have 'short' names but expand to several or indeed many lines of code, they can be used to make assembly language programs appear to be far shorter, requiring fewer lines of source code, as with higher level languages.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] They can also be used to add higher levels of structure to assembly programs, optionally introduce embedded debugging code via parameters and other similar features.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Macro assemblers often allow macros to take parameters.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Thus a macro might generate numerous assembly language instructions or data definitions, based on the macro arguments.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This could be used to generate record-style data structures or "unrolled" loops, for example, or could generate entire algorithms based on complex parameters.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] For instance, a "sort" macro could accept the specification of a complex sort key and generate code crafted for that specific key, not needing the run-time tests that would be required for a general procedure interpreting the specification.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] An organization using assembly language that has been heavily extended using such a macro suite can be considered to be working in a higher-level language since such programmers are not working with a computer's lowest-level conceptual elements.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Underlining this point, macros were used to implement an early virtual machine in SNOBOL4 (1967), which was written in the SNOBOL Implementation Language (SIL), an assembly language for a virtual machine.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The target machine would translate this to its native code using a macro assembler.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This allowed a high degree of portability for the time.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Macros were used to customize large scale software systems for specific customers in the mainframe era and were also used by customer personnel to satisfy their employers' needs by making specific versions of manufacturer operating systems.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] IBM OS/360 uses macros to perform system generation.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The user specifies options by coding a series of assembler macros.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Assembling these macros generates a job stream to build the system, including job control language and utility control statements.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This is because, as was realized in the 1960s, the concept of "macro processing" is independent of the concept of "assembly", the former being in modern terms more word processing, text processing, than generating object code.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The concept of macro processing appeared, and appears, in the C programming language, which supports "preprocessor instructions" to set variables, and make conditional tests on their values.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Unlike certain previous macro processors inside assemblers, the C preprocessor is not Turing-complete because it lacks the ability to either loop or "go to", the latter allowing programs to loop.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Despite the power of macro processing, it fell into disuse in many high level languages (major exceptions being C, C++ and PL/I) while remaining a perennial for assemblers.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Macro parameter substitution is strictly by name: at macro processing time, the value of a parameter is textually substituted for its name.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The most famous class of bugs resulting was the use of a parameter that itself was an expression and not a simple name when the macro writer expected a name.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] the intention was that the caller would provide the name of a variable, and the "global" variable or constant b would be used to multiply "a".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] If foo is called with the parameter `a-c`, the macro expansion of `load a-c*b` occurs.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] To avoid any possible ambiguity, users of macro processors can parenthesize formal parameters inside macro definitions, or callers can parenthesize the input parameters.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Packages of macros have been written providing structured programming elements to encode execution flow.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The earliest example of this approach was in the Concept-14 macro set, originally proposed by Harlan Mills (March 1970), and implemented by Marvin Kessler at IBM's Federal Systems Division, which provided IF/ELSE/ENDIF and similar control flow blocks for OS/360 assembler programs.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This was a way to reduce or eliminate the use of GOTO operations in assembly code, one of the main factors causing spaghetti code in assembly language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] This approach was widely accepted in the early 1980s (the latter days of large-scale assembly language use).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] IBM's High Level Assembler Toolkit includes such a macro package.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Another design was A-Natural, a "stream-oriented" assembler for 8080/Z80 processors from Whitesmiths Ltd.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] (developers of the Unix-like Idris operating system, and what was reported to be the first commercial C compiler).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] The language was classified as an assembler because it worked with raw machine elements such as opcodes, registers, and memory references; but it incorporated an expression syntax to indicate execution order.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] Parentheses and other special symbols, along with block-oriented structured programming constructs, controlled the sequence of the generated instructions.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] A-natural was built as the object language of a C compiler, rather than for hand-coding, but its logical syntax won some fans.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] There has been little apparent demand for more sophisticated assemblers since the decline of large-scale assembly language development.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p01] In spite of that, they are still being developed and applied in cases where resource constraints or peculiarities in the target system's architecture prevent the effective use of higher-level languages.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] When the stored-program computer was introduced, programs were written in machine code, and loaded into the computer from punched paper tape or toggled directly into memory from console switches.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] In late 1948, the Electronic Delay Storage Automatic Calculator (EDSAC) had an assembler (named "initial orders") integrated into its bootstrap program.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] It used one-letter mnemonics developed by David Wheeler, who is credited by the IEEE Computer Society as the creator of the first "assembler".
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Reports on the EDSAC introduced the term "assembly" for the process of combining fields into an instruction word.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] SOAP (Symbolic Optimal Assembly Program) was an assembly language for the IBM 650 computer written by Stan Poley in 1955.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Assembly languages eliminated much of the error-prone, tedious, and time-consuming first-generation programming needed with the earliest computers, freeing programmers from tedium such as remembering numeric codes and calculating addresses.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] They were once widely used for all sorts of programming.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] By the late 1950s their use had largely been supplanted by higher-level languages in the search for improved programming productivity.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Today, assembly language is still used for direct hardware manipulation, access to specialized processor instructions, or to address critical performance issues.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Typical uses are device drivers, low-level embedded systems, and real-time systems (see § Current usage).
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Numerous programs were written entirely in assembly language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] The Burroughs MCP (1961) was the first computer for which an operating system was not developed entirely in assembly language; it was written in Executive Systems Problem Oriented Language (ESPOL), an Algol dialect.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Many commercial applications were written in assembly language as well, including a large amount of the IBM mainframe software developed by large corporations.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] COBOL, FORTRAN and some PL/I eventually displaced assembly language, although a number of large organizations retained assembly-language application infrastructures well into the 1990s.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the primary development language for 8-bit home computers such as the Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, ZX Spectrum, and Commodore 64.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Interpreted BASIC on these systems did not offer maximum execution speed and full use of facilities to take full advantage of the available hardware.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language was the default choice for programming 8-bit consoles such as the Atari 2600 and Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Key software for IBM PC compatibles such as MS-DOS, Turbo Pascal, and the Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet was written in assembly language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] As computer speed grew exponentially, assembly language became a tool for speeding up parts of programs, such as the rendering of *Doom*, rather than a dominant development language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] In the 1990s, assembly language was used to maximise performance from systems such as the Sega Saturn, and as the primary language for arcade hardware using the TMS34010 integrated CPU/GPU such as *Mortal Kombat* and *NBA Jam*.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] There has been debate over the usefulness and performance of assembly language relative to high-level languages.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Although assembly language has specific niche uses where it is important (see below), there are other tools for optimization.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] As of July 2017, the TIOBE index of programming language popularity ranks assembly language at 11, ahead of Visual Basic, for example.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Assembler can be used to optimize for speed or optimize for size.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] In the case of speed optimization, modern optimizing compilers are claimed to render high-level languages into code that can run as fast as hand-written assembly, despite some counter-examples.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] The complexity of modern processors and memory sub-systems makes effective optimization increasingly difficult for compilers and assembly programmers alike.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Increasing processor performance has meant that most CPUs sit idle most of the time, with delays caused by predictable bottlenecks such as cache misses, I/O operations and paging, making raw code execution speed a non-issue for many programmers.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Assembly language is still taught in most computer science and electronic engineering programs.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Although few programmers today regularly work with assembly language as a tool, the underlying concepts remain important.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Such fundamental topics as binary arithmetic, memory allocation, stack processing, character set encoding, interrupt processing, and compiler design would be hard to study in detail without a grasp of how a computer operates at the hardware level.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Since a computer's behaviour is fundamentally defined by its instruction set, the logical way to learn such concepts is to study an assembly language.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Most modern computers have similar instruction sets.
[src:board-support-package/assembly-language-p02] Therefore, studying a single assembly language is sufficient to learn the basic concepts, recognize situations where the use of assembly language might be appropriate, and to see how efficient executable code can be created from high-level languages.
[src:board-support-package/barebox] The Barebox project began in July 2007 as u-boot-v2, as it was derived from Das U-Boot, but with heavier borrowings from Linux like similar utilities and with a more Linux-like coding style.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:board-support-package/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:board-support-package/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:board-support-package/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:board-support-package/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:board-support-package/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:board-support-package/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:board-support-package/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:board-support-package/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:board-support-package/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:board-support-package/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:board-support-package/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:board-support-package/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:board-support-package/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:board-support-package/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:board-support-package/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:board-support-package/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:board-support-package/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:board-support-package/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:board-support-package/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:board-support-package/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:board-support-package/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:board-support-package/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:board-support-package/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:board-support-package/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:board-support-package/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:board-support-package/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:board-support-package/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:board-support-package/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:board-support-package/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:board-support-package/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:board-support-package/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:board-support-package/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:board-support-package/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:board-support-package/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:board-support-package/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:board-support-package/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:board-support-package/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:board-support-package/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:board-support-package/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:board-support-package/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:board-support-package/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:board-support-package/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:board-support-package/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:board-support-package/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:board-support-package/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:board-support-package/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:board-support-package/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:board-support-package/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:board-support-package/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:board-support-package/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:board-support-package/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:board-support-package/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:board-support-package/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:board-support-package/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:board-support-package/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:board-support-package/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:board-support-package/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:board-support-package/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:board-support-package/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:board-support-package/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:board-support-package/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:board-support-package/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:board-support-package/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:board-support-package/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:board-support-package/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:board-support-package/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:board-support-package/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:board-support-package/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:board-support-package/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:board-support-package/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:board-support-package/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:board-support-package/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:board-support-package/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:board-support-package/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:board-support-package/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:board-support-package/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:board-support-package/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:board-support-package/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
